description: From Old French movable. Surface etymology is move +â€Ž -able.

adjectives.description: movable (comparative more movable, superlative most movable)

entries.meaning: Capable of being moved, lifted, carried, drawn, turned, or conveyed, or in any way made to change place or posture; not fixed or stationary
examples: The owners had supplied the vessel with a movable derrick for the purpose of raising the gangways of the vessel when in port, in order to discharge cargo.

entries.meaning: Changing from one time to another
examples: This feast is movable - its date varies from year to year.

entries.meaning: Something which is movable; an article of wares or goods; a commodity; a piece of property not fixed, or not a part of real estate; generally, in the plural, goods; wares; furniture.
